<p level="4" style="Preformatted Text" xid="1881"><field type="list_label" xid="1882"></field><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; dom-dir:ltr; margin-bottom:0.0598in; lang:en-US; default-tab-interval:0.4925in; margin-top:0.0598in">	Jennings Project</c></p>
<p level="4" xid="1883"><field type="list_label" xid="1884"></field><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; dom-dir:ltr; margin-bottom:0.0598in; lang:en-US; default-tab-interval:0.4925in; margin-top:0.0598in">	What is the name of Ubuntus own GUI compositor replacement for X? (Just the name)</c></p>
<p level="4" xid="1885"><field type="list_label" xid="1886"></field><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; dom-dir:ltr; margin-bottom:0.0598in; lang:en-US; default-tab-interval:0.4925in; margin-top:0.0598in">	There are 5 types of Linux window managers: Compositing, Minimalistic, Tiling, and Other.<br/>What is the name of the missing category?</c></p>
<p level="4" xid="1887"><field type="list_label" xid="1888"></field><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; dom-dir:ltr; margin-bottom:0.0598in; lang:en-US; default-tab-interval:0.4925in; margin-top:0.0598in">	There are 4 major Linux desktop environments in use today: which grouping is correct?</c></p>
<p level="4" style="Preformatted Text" xid="1889"><field type="list_label" xid="1890"></field><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; dom-dir:ltr; margin-bottom:0.0598in; lang:en-US; default-tab-interval:0.4925in; margin-top:0.0598in">	KDE, GNOME, CDE, LXDE</c></p>
<p level="4" style="Preformatted Text" xid="1891"><field type="list_label" xid="1892"></field><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; dom-dir:ltr; margin-bottom:0.0598in; lang:en-US; default-tab-interval:0.4925in; margin-top:0.0598in">	KDE, GNOME, E17, GNUSTEP</c></p>
<p level="4" style="Preformatted Text" xid="1893"><field type="list_label" xid="1894"></field><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; dom-dir:ltr; margin-bottom:0.0598in; lang:en-US; default-tab-interval:0.4925in; margin-top:0.0598in">	KDE, GNOME, X, LXDE</c></p>
<p level="4" style="Preformatted Text" xid="1895"><field type="list_label" xid="1896"></field><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; dom-dir:ltr; margin-bottom:0.0598in; lang:en-US; default-tab-interval:0.4925in; margin-top:0.0598in">	KDE, GNOME, Xfce, LXDE</c></p>
<p level="4" xid="1897"><field type="list_label" xid="1898"></field><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; dom-dir:ltr; margin-bottom:0.0598in; lang:en-US; default-tab-interval:0.4925in; margin-top:0.0598in">	What is the name of the windowing toolkit that KDE uses? (Two letters)</c></p>
<p level="4" xid="1899"><field type="list_label" xid="1900"></field><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; dom-dir:ltr; margin-bottom:0.0598in; lang:en-US; default-tab-interval:0.4925in; margin-top:0.0598in">	What is the name of the windowing toolkit that GNOME uses? (just 3 letters, no plus sign)</c></p>
<p level="4" xid="1901"><field type="list_label" xid="1902"></field><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; dom-dir:ltr; margin-bottom:0.0598in; lang:en-US; default-tab-interval:0.4925in; margin-top:0.0598in">	What is the name of the founder of the GNOME project?</c></p>
<p level="4" xid="1903"><field type="list_label" xid="1904"></field><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; dom-dir:ltr; margin-bottom:0.0598in; lang:en-US; default-tab-interval:0.4925in; margin-top:0.0598in">	When the GNOME 3 desktop environment was released in early 2012, many people were unhappy that many changes were made. There were 3 major projects started to either preserve GNOME 2 or to modify GNOME 3 significantly  what are the names of those projects?</c></p>
<p level="4" style="Preformatted Text" xid="1905"><field type="list_label" xid="1906"></field><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; dom-dir:ltr; margin-bottom:0.0598in; lang:en-US; default-tab-interval:0.4925in; margin-top:0.0598in">	Enlightenment, LXDE, Xfce</c></p>
<p level="4" style="Preformatted Text" xid="1907"><field type="list_label" xid="1908"></field><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; dom-dir:ltr; margin-bottom:0.0598in; lang:en-US; default-tab-interval:0.4925in; margin-top:0.0598in">	Mint, Unity, Mate</c></p>
<p level="4" style="Preformatted Text" xid="1909"><field type="list_label" xid="1910"></field><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; dom-dir:ltr; margin-bottom:0.0598in; lang:en-US; default-tab-interval:0.4925in; margin-top:0.0598in">	Unity, Mate, Cinnamon</c></p>
<p level="4" style="Preformatted Text" xid="1911"><field type="list_label" xid="1912"></field><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; dom-dir:ltr; margin-bottom:0.0598in; lang:en-US; default-tab-interval:0.4925in; margin-top:0.0598in">	Cinnamon, Mint, Mate</c></p>
<p level="4" xid="1913"><field type="list_label" xid="1914"></field><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; dom-dir:ltr; margin-bottom:0.0598in; lang:en-US; default-tab-interval:0.4925in; margin-top:0.0598in">	When released in 2006, what was the main development goal of the LXDE desktop environment?</c></p>
<p level="4" style="Preformatted Text" xid="1915"><field type="list_label" xid="1916"></field><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; dom-dir:ltr; margin-bottom:0.0598in; lang:en-US; default-tab-interval:0.4925in; margin-top:0.0598in">	GUI desktop features</c></p>
<p level="4" style="Preformatted Text" xid="1917"><field type="list_label" xid="1918"></field><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; dom-dir:ltr; margin-bottom:0.0598in; lang:en-US; default-tab-interval:0.4925in; margin-top:0.0598in">	Multi-desktop paradigm</c></p>
<p level="4" style="Preformatted Text" xid="1919"><field type="list_label" xid="1920"></field><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; dom-dir:ltr; margin-bottom:0.0598in; lang:en-US; default-tab-interval:0.4925in; margin-top:0.0598in">	Energy saving and extremely fast </c></p>
<p level="4" style="Preformatted Text" xid="1921"><field type="list_label" xid="1922"></field><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; dom-dir:ltr; margin-bottom:0.0598in; lang:en-US; default-tab-interval:0.4925in; margin-top:0.0598in">	Made for high end gaming systems</c></p>
<p level="4" xid="1923"><field type="list_label" xid="1924"></field><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; dom-dir:ltr; margin-bottom:0.0598in; lang:en-US; default-tab-interval:0.4925in; margin-top:0.0598in">	Which of these statements are true in regards to Linux desktop environments? (choose all that apply)</c></p>
<p level="4" style="Preformatted Text" xid="1925"><field type="list_label" xid="1926"></field><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; dom-dir:ltr; margin-bottom:0.0598in; lang:en-US; default-tab-interval:0.4925in; margin-top:0.0598in">	Desktop environments have a File Manager</c></p>
<p level="4" style="Preformatted Text" xid="1927"><field type="list_label" xid="1928"></field><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; dom-dir:ltr; margin-bottom:0.0598in; lang:en-US; default-tab-interval:0.4925in; margin-top:0.0598in">	Desktop Environments have start or action buttons and task and notification bars </c></p>
<p level="4" style="Preformatted Text" xid="1929"><field type="list_label" xid="1930"></field><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; dom-dir:ltr; margin-bottom:0.0598in; lang:en-US; default-tab-interval:0.4925in; margin-top:0.0598in">	Desktop environments have a changeable but consistent look-and-feel</c></p>
<p level="4" style="Preformatted Text" xid="1931"><field type="list_label" xid="1932"></field><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; dom-dir:ltr; margin-bottom:0.0598in; lang:en-US; default-tab-interval:0.4925in; margin-top:0.0598in">	Desktop environments have system configuration tools and user applications built in</c></p>
<p level="4" style="Preformatted Text" xid="1933"><field type="list_label" xid="1934"></field><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; dom-dir:ltr; margin-bottom:0.0598in; lang:en-US; default-tab-interval:0.4925in; margin-top:0.0598in">	Desktop environments have lower memory requirements than window managers</c></p>
<p level="4" xid="1935"><field type="list_label" xid="1936"></field><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; dom-dir:ltr; margin-bottom:0.0598in; lang:en-US; default-tab-interval:0.4925in; margin-top:0.0598in">	What is the default desktop environment for Fedora 22? (Name and versions)</c></p>
<p level="4" xid="1937"><field type="list_label" xid="1938"></field><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; dom-dir:ltr; margin-bottom:0.0598in; lang:en-US; default-tab-interval:0.4925in; margin-top:0.0598in">	What is the name of the button on the upper left hand corner of the GNOME 3 desktop in Fedora 22 that you use to launch applications?</c></p>
<p level="4" xid="1939"><field type="list_label" xid="1940"></field><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; dom-dir:ltr; margin-bottom:0.0598in; lang:en-US; default-tab-interval:0.4925in; margin-top:0.0598in">	What is the name of the default Ubuntu desktop environment?</c></p>
<p style="Heading 3" xid="1941"><c props="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt; dom-dir:ltr; margin-bottom:0.0598in; lang:en-US; default-tab-interval:0.4925in; margin-top:0.0598in">Podcast Questions</c></p>
