<p style="Normal" xid="3796">TBA</p>
<p style="Heading 2" xid="3797">Chapter 03</p>
<p style="Normal" xid="3798">Hardware and Linux Installation Chapter 03</p>
<p level="3" xid="3799"><field type="list_label" xid="3800"></field>	What is the term for the industry standard file format that is used to install a Linux distro?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3801"><field type="list_label" xid="3802"></field>	ISO</p>
<p level="3" xid="3803"><field type="list_label" xid="3804"></field>	What is currently the most common Linux install media type?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3805"><field type="list_label" xid="3806"></field>	USB</p>
<p level="3" xid="3807"><field type="list_label" xid="3808"></field>	What is the name of the most common tool used to create bootable Linux install media?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3809"><field type="list_label" xid="3810"></field>	UNetbootin</p>
<p level="3" xid="3811"><field type="list_label" xid="3812"></field>	What is the technology that is inserted between ring 1 and ring 0 that enables virtualization? A: hypervisor</p>
<p level="3" xid="3813"><field type="list_label" xid="3814"></field>	The operating system that the hypervisor resides on is called the _________ system? A: host</p>
<p level="3" xid="3815"><field type="list_label" xid="3816"></field>	Hosted or desktop virtualization is called what type of hypervisor? A: Type II</p>
<p level="3" xid="3817"><field type="list_label" xid="3818"></field>	Bare Metal or Native Virtualization is called what type of hypervisor? A: Type I</p>
<p level="3" xid="3819"><field type="list_label" xid="3820"></field>	Each Linux installation distro provides a mechanism to compare what you downloaded with what you expected to download, what is that called?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3821"><field type="list_label" xid="3822"></field>	check sum</p>
<p level="3" xid="3823"><field type="list_label" xid="3824"></field>	What is the name of the driver package you can install in VirtualBox in order to enable features such as shared clipboard, larger screen resolution, and mouse pointer integration?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3825"><field type="list_label" xid="3826"></field>	VirtualBox Guest Additions</p>
<p level="3" xid="3827"><field type="list_label" xid="3828"></field>	What is the name for a Linux installation that runs in memory?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3829"><field type="list_label" xid="3830"></field>	Live ISO</p>
<p style="Heading 2" xid="3831">Chapter 04</p>
<p style="Normal" xid="3832">Linux Desktop and GUI Chapter 04 review questions</p>
<p level="3" xid="3833"><field type="list_label" xid="3834"></field>	What was the original and most popular Unix Smart Terminal?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3835"><field type="list_label" xid="3836"></field>	VT-100</p>
<p level="3" xid="3837"><field type="list_label" xid="3838"></field>	What is the three letter abbreviation still in use today in modern Linux to refer to terminal devices?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3839"><field type="list_label" xid="3840"></field>	TTY</p>
<p level="3" xid="3841"><field type="list_label" xid="3842"></field>	Why is the GNOME terminal and Windows cmd.exe terminal emulator screens 80 by 25 by default?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3843"><field type="list_label" xid="3844"></field>	The developers of these technologies were seeking to emulate the popular VT-100 and VT-0220 terminals they used prior.</p>
<p level="3" xid="3845"><field type="list_label" xid="3846"></field>	What is the key combo sequence you can hit to switch to a new virtual terminal in Linux?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3847"><field type="list_label" xid="3848"></field>	Alt + Ctrl + F1 - F7</p>
<p level="3" xid="3849"><field type="list_label" xid="3850"></field>	What is the name of the original Unix based GUI that came out of MIT in ~1984?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3851"><field type="list_label" xid="3852"></field>	X</p>
<p level="3" xid="3853"><field type="list_label" xid="3854"></field>	True or False  X was originally not opensourced by MIT in 1984</p>
<p level="3" xid="3855"><field type="list_label" xid="3856"></field>	False</p>
<p level="3" xid="3857"><field type="list_label" xid="3858"></field>	What is the official name in the Ubuntu Unity desktop environment for the launcher icon? (The Icon in the upper left hand corner that looks like circle with 3 dots?)</p>
<p level="3" xid="3859"><field type="list_label" xid="3860"></field>	Dash Icon</p>
<p level="3" xid="3861"><field type="list_label" xid="3862"></field>	What is the name of the successor GUI compositor to X being created by the X.org foundation?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3863"><field type="list_label" xid="3864"></field>	Wayland Project</p>
<p level="3" xid="3865"><field type="list_label" xid="3866"></field>	What is the name of Ubuntus own GUI compositor replacement for X? (Just the name)</p>
<p level="3" xid="3867"><field type="list_label" xid="3868"></field>	Mir</p>
<p level="3" xid="3869"><field type="list_label" xid="3870"></field>	There are 5 types of Linux window managers: Compositing, Minimalistic, Tiling, and Other.<br/>What is the name of the missing category?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3871"><field type="list_label" xid="3872"></field>	Stacking</p>
<p level="3" xid="3873"><field type="list_label" xid="3874"></field>	There are 4 major Linux desktop environments in use today: which grouping is correct?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3875"><field type="list_label" xid="3876"></field>	KDE, GNOME, Xfce, LXDE</p>
<p level="3" xid="3877"><field type="list_label" xid="3878"></field>	What is the name of the windowing toolkit that KDE uses? (Two letters)</p>
<p level="3" xid="3879"><field type="list_label" xid="3880"></field>	Qt</p>
<p level="3" xid="3881"><field type="list_label" xid="3882"></field>	What is the name of the windowing toolkit that GNOME uses? (just 3 letters, no plus sign)</p>
<p level="3" xid="3883"><field type="list_label" xid="3884"></field>	GTK+</p>
<p level="3" xid="3885"><field type="list_label" xid="3886"></field>	What is the name of the founder of the GNOME project?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3887"><field type="list_label" xid="3888"></field>	Miguel de Icaza</p>
<p level="3" xid="3889"><field type="list_label" xid="3890"></field>	When the GNOME 3 desktop environment was released in early 2012, many people were unhappy that many changes were made. There were 3 major projects started to either preserve GNOME 2 or to modify GNOME 3 significantly  what are the names of those projects?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3891"><field type="list_label" xid="3892"></field>	Unity, Mate, Cinnamon</p>
<p level="3" xid="3893"><field type="list_label" xid="3894"></field>	When released in 2006, what was the main development goal of the LXDE desktop environment?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3895"><field type="list_label" xid="3896"></field>	Energy saving and extremely fast</p>
<p level="3" xid="3897"><field type="list_label" xid="3898"></field>	Which of these statements are true in regards to Linux desktop environments? (choose all that apply)</p>
<p level="3" xid="3899"><field type="list_label" xid="3900"></field>	Desktop environments have a File Manager</p>
<p level="3" xid="3901"><field type="list_label" xid="3902"></field>	Desktop Environments have start or action buttons and task and notification bars</p>
<p level="3" xid="3903"><field type="list_label" xid="3904"></field>	Desktop environments have a changeable but consistent look-and-feel</p>
<p level="3" xid="3905"><field type="list_label" xid="3906"></field>	Desktop environments have system configuration tools and user applications built in</p>
<p level="3" xid="3907"><field type="list_label" xid="3908"></field>	What is the default desktop environment for Fedora 22? (Name and versions)</p>
<p level="3" xid="3909"><field type="list_label" xid="3910"></field>	GNOME 3</p>
<p level="3" xid="3911"><field type="list_label" xid="3912"></field>	What is the name of the button on the upper left hand corner of the GNOME 3 desktop in Fedora 22 that you use to launch applications?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3913"><field type="list_label" xid="3914"></field>	Activities</p>
<p level="3" xid="3915"><field type="list_label" xid="3916"></field>	What is the name of the default Ubuntu desktop environment?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3917"><field type="list_label" xid="3918"></field>	Unity</p>
<p style="Heading 2" xid="3919">Chapter 05</p>
<p style="Normal" xid="3920">The Linux Filesystem, Path, Shell, and File Permissions Chapter 05 review questions</p>
<p level="3" xid="3921"><field type="list_label" xid="3922"></field>	What is the numeric value of a file with the permissions rwxr--r--?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3923"><field type="list_label" xid="3924"></field>	744</p>
<p level="3" xid="3925"><field type="list_label" xid="3926"></field>	What is the numeric value of a file with the permissions rw-----?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3927"><field type="list_label" xid="3928"></field>	600</p>
<p level="3" xid="3929"><field type="list_label" xid="3930"></field>	What is the numeric value of a file with the permission rwx-r-xr-x?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3931"><field type="list_label" xid="3932"></field>	755</p>
<p level="3" xid="3933"><field type="list_label" xid="3934"></field>	What is the name of the command you use to list the contents of a directory?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3935"><field type="list_label" xid="3936"></field>	ls</p>
<p level="3" xid="3937"><field type="list_label" xid="3938"></field>	What is the name of the command you use to display the content of a file to the screen?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3939"><field type="list_label" xid="3940"></field>	cat</p>
<p level="3" xid="3941"><field type="list_label" xid="3942"></field>	What is the name of the command you use to display the content of a file to the screen that allows you to page up and down?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3943"><field type="list_label" xid="3944"></field>	less</p>
<p level="3" xid="3945"><field type="list_label" xid="3946"></field>	Every shell command has three components:</p>
<p level="3" xid="3947"><field type="list_label" xid="3948"></field>	Command, options, arguments</p>
<p level="3" xid="3949"><field type="list_label" xid="3950"></field>	What does the user use to issue commands to the kernel?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3951"><field type="list_label" xid="3952"></field>	Shell</p>
<p level="3" xid="3953"><field type="list_label" xid="3954"></field>	What is the name of the GNU shell that is standard across all Linux Distros</p>
<p level="3" xid="3955"><field type="list_label" xid="3956"></field>	bash</p>
<p level="3" xid="3957"><field type="list_label" xid="3958"></field>	Based on the ls command, what is the option to do a long listing?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3959"><field type="list_label" xid="3960"></field>	ls l</p>
<p level="3" xid="3961"><field type="list_label" xid="3962"></field>	What is the command you can use to find out additional usage information about a shell command?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3963"><field type="list_label" xid="3964"></field>	man</p>
<p level="3" xid="3965"><field type="list_label" xid="3966"></field>	Which of these directories is not part of the LSB LFH?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3967"><field type="list_label" xid="3968"></field>	temp</p>
<p level="3" xid="3969"><field type="list_label" xid="3970"></field>	The Linux Filesystem is an upside down what?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3971"><field type="list_label" xid="3972"></field>	tree</p>
<p level="3" xid="3973"><field type="list_label" xid="3974"></field>	What is the name of the top of the Linux Filesystem?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3975"><field type="list_label" xid="3976"></field>	/</p>
<p level="3" xid="3977"><field type="list_label" xid="3978"></field>	Everything (directories, files, devices) in Unix/Linux is a what?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3979"><field type="list_label" xid="3980"></field>	file</p>
<p level="3" xid="3981"><field type="list_label" xid="3982"></field>	What is the name of the Unix system standard developed in ~1985 that defines at a minimum what a certified Unix based system must support?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3983"><field type="list_label" xid="3984"></field>	POSIX</p>
<p level="3" xid="3985"><field type="list_label" xid="3986"></field>	What is the directory where all configuration files are stored in Linux?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3987"><field type="list_label" xid="3988"></field>	etc</p>
<p level="3" xid="3989"><field type="list_label" xid="3990"></field>	What is the directory where all system binaries are stored?</p>
<p level="3" xid="3991"><field type="list_label" xid="3992"></field>	bin</p>
<p level="3" xid="3993"><field type="list_label" xid="3994"></field>	What is the directory that holds all of the users home directories? (no slash, just the name)</p>
<p level="3" xid="3995"><field type="list_label" xid="3996"></field>	home</p>
<p level="3" xid="3997"><field type="list_label" xid="3998"></field>	True or False - Leonart Poettering supports POSIX</p>
<p level="3" xid="3999"><field type="list_label" xid="4000"></field>	False</p>
<p style="Heading 2" xid="4001">Chapter 06</p>
